Section 3.8.1: all exercises

1.) What is the problem with this plot? How could you improve it?

This plot is lacking x and y-axis labels and units of measure so I would label these. The data also have many repeated rounded values leading to overplotting so you could add the jitter option to add noise.The plot as is also does not differentiate between any type of car which may be helpful to see- we can add this visually by adding color by class of car.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy, color=class)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_jitter() +
  xlab("City miles per gallon") +
  ylab("Highway miles per gallon")

2.) What parameters to geom_jitter() control the amount of jittering?

The geom_jitter() geom is shorthand for geom_point(position = jitter) and creates a random amount of jittering, therefore does not require parameters to control the amount of jittering. However, by adding position = position_jitter() and using the width and height parameters you can control the amount of vertical and horizontal jitter. Setting a random seed number in the Seed parameter will make this jitter reproducible, as seen in the different exmaples below.

#?geom_jitter
#?position_jitter
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy, color=class)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_jitter(position = position_jitter(width = 5, height = 2, seed = 4576)) +
  xlab("City miles per gallon") +
  ylab("Highway miles per gallon") 

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy, color=class)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_jitter(position = position_jitter(width = 2, height = 6, seed = 4575)) +
  xlab("City miles per gallon") +
  ylab("Highway miles per gallon")

3.) Compare and contrast geom_jitter() with geom_count().

The geom_jitter geom randomly adds noise to separate overlapping points created by overplotting, whereas the geom_count geom increases the size of the point on the plot dependent on how many overlapping points are sharing the same spot, as well as adds a legend to define the sizes of the points.

#?geom_jitter
#?geom_count

#examples from help pages:
ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, hwy)) +
 geom_jitter()

ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, hwy)) +
 geom_count()

4.) Whats the default position adjustment for geom_boxplot()? Create a visualisation of the mpg dataset that demonstrates it.

The default position for geom_boxplot() is position=dodge, demonstrated by the below:

#?geom_boxplot()
#default
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

#same
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_boxplot(position="dodge")

2.) What does labs() do? Read the documentation.

Labs() enables you to modify the labels of axes, legends, and plots by using any or all of the arguments title, subtitle, caption, tag, or label.

#?labs()

4.) What does the plot below tell you about the relationship between city and highway mpg? Why is coord_fixed() important? What does geom_abline() do?

This plot tells us that city and highway mpg are correlated in such a way that highway mpg increases as city mpg increases. Coord_fixed() fixes the aspect ratio so that the units on the y-axis are equivalent to that on the x-axis, otherwise the units of the x-axis make this plot look much wider. Geom_abline() adds a reference line to the plot controlled by slope and intercept.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline() +
  coord_fixed()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline()

#?coord_fixed()
#?geom_abline()

3.) How many flights have a missing dep_time? What other variables are missing? What might these rows represent?

336,776 flights have a missing departure time.

length(is.na(flights$dep_time))
## [1] 336776

4.) Why is NA ^ 0 not missing? Why is NA | TRUE not missing? Why is FALSE & NA not missing? Can you figure out the general rule? (NA * 0 is a tricky counterexample!)

As opposed to other programming languages that consider missing values to be an actually value (for example: in SAS missings are a very small negative number), in R NA can be thought of as an unknown value so any operation that you perform on an unknown value where operations that involve comparisons cannot be used.

is.na(NA^0)
## [1] FALSE
is.na(NA|TRUE)
## [1] FALSE
is.na(FALSE & NA)
## [1] FALSE
is.na(NA*0)
## [1] TRUE

3.) What does the one_of() function do? Why might it be helpful in conjunction with this vector?

The one_of() function is a helper function that can be used with the select function which defines variables within a vector. This could be useful if you are wanting to perform an operation using the select function only on a defined subset of variables.

vars <- c("year", "month", "day", "dep_delay", "arr_delay")

select(flights, one_of(vars))
## # A tibble: 336,776 x 5
